NOTES_COLOSSIANS = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Apostolos" (ἀπόστολος, G652) denotes one sent with full authority, a commissioned envoy. Paul places his apostolic authority as derived "through the will of God" (διὰ θελήματος θεοῦ), establishing divine mandate before addressing the Colossian heresy.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The triad of faith (v4), love (v4), and hope (v5) appears here with hope (ἐλπίς, G1680) as the foundational cause — faith and love flow from the certain hope stored in heaven. This differs from 1 Cor 13:13 where love is supreme; here the eschatological reserve of hope grounds present faithfulness.',
        9: 'GREEK: "Epignōsis" (ἐπίγνωσις, G1922) is an intensified form of "gnōsis" (knowledge), meaning full, experiential, or precise knowledge. Paul deliberately uses this stronger term against the proto-gnostic claims at Colossae, asserting that true full knowledge comes through Christ alone, not through esoteric spiritual speculation.',
        13: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "The authority of the darkness" (ἐξουσία τοῦ σκότους) refers to the ruling power of the domain of hostile spiritual beings. God\'s act of "transferring" (μεθίστημι, G3179) believers into Christ\'s kingdom echoes the divine council motif where God reassigns the nations from rebellious elohim (Deut 32:8-9 LXX) to the rule of his Son. The "kingdom of the Son of his love" stands in direct contrast to the dominion of fallen powers.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Image" (εἰκών, G1504) echoes Gen 1:26-27 LXX — Christ is the perfect and original image of the invisible God that Adam was meant to reflect. "Firstborn of all creation" (πρωτότοκος πάσης κτίσεως) denotes supremacy and preeminence of rank, not temporal origin, as v16 immediately clarifies: all things were created in him. TYPOLOGY: Christ as the true "image of God" fulfills and surpasses the Adamic vocation (Gen 1:26; 2 Cor 4:4).',
        16: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The list "thrones, dominions, rulers, authorities" (θρόνοι, κυριότητες, ἀρχαί, ἐξουσίαι) names ranks within the heavenly hierarchy — both loyal and rebellious spiritual beings. All were created in, through, and unto Christ. This directly counters Colossian angel-veneration by subordinating every heavenly power to Christ\'s creative sovereignty.',
        18: 'GREEK: "Prōteuōn" (πρωτεύων, G4409) is a NT hapax legomenon, meaning "holding first place" or "having preeminence." Combined with "archē" (beginning/origin) and "firstborn from the dead," Paul establishes Christ\'s absolute supremacy in both creation and new creation. TYPOLOGY: As firstborn from the dead, Christ inaugurates the eschatological resurrection, fulfilling the firstfruits typology (cf. 1 Cor 15:20).',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Plērōma" (πλήρωμα, G4138) — "fullness" — is a key term Paul likely reclaims from proto-gnostic vocabulary at Colossae. Rather than the divine fullness being distributed among emanations or aeons, all the fullness was pleased to permanently dwell in Christ alone. The verb "eudokeō" (was pleased) implies the Father\'s sovereign will and delight in this arrangement.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Apokatallassō" (ἀποκαταλλάσσω, G604) is a double-compounded verb unique to Paul (also Eph 2:16), intensifying the concept of reconciliation. The scope is cosmic — "all things" whether on earth or in the heavens — accomplished through the blood of the cross. This cosmic reconciliation includes the subjugation of hostile powers and the restoration of all creation under Christ\'s headship (cf. Eph 1:10).',
        24: 'GREEK: "Antanaplēroō" (ἀνταναπληρόω, G466) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "to fill up in return what is lacking." Paul does not suggest Christ\'s atoning work is incomplete, but that the apostolic vocation of suffering for the sake of the church-body participates in the ongoing pattern of Christ\'s afflictions (θλίψεις, not his sacrificial death). THEOLOGICAL: This distinguishes redemptive suffering (complete in Christ alone) from ministerial suffering (the apostle\'s share in proclaiming and embodying the gospel).',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Mystērion" (μυστήριον, G3466) denotes not an unsolvable puzzle but a divine plan once hidden and now revealed. The mystery hidden from the ages and generations has a specific content revealed in v27: Christ among the nations. This disclosure marks the eschatological turning point — God\'s secret counsel for Gentile inclusion is now made manifest to his saints (cf. Eph 3:4-6; Rom 16:25-26).',
        27: 'TYPOLOGY: "Christ in you, the hope of glory" is the apex of the mystery — the indwelling presence of Christ among the Gentile nations fulfills the OT promises that God\'s glory would extend to all peoples (Isa 49:6; Ps 72:19). The phrase also echoes the tabernacle/temple motif: God\'s glorious presence now dwells not in a structure but in his people through the Messiah.',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'GREEK: "Mystery of God, that is, Christ" (τοῦ μυστηρίου τοῦ θεοῦ, Χριστοῦ) — the textual tradition varies here, but the best reading makes Christ himself the content of God\'s mystery. "Symbibasthentes" (συμβιβασθέντες, Strong\'s G4822) means "knit together, united," carrying the sense of being instructed and compacted into unity. THEOLOGICAL: The "full assurance of understanding" (πληροφορία τῆς συνέσεως) stands in deliberate contrast to the false "philosophy" warned against in v.8—true knowledge is found exclusively in Christ (Eph 3:3-4).',
        8: 'GREEK: "Sylagōgōn" (συλαγωγῶν, Strong\'s G4812) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "to carry off as plunder/spoil," depicting false teachers as spiritual kidnappers. "Pithanologia" (πιθανολογία, v.4, G4086) is also a hapax. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Stoicheia tou kosmou" (στοιχεῖα τοῦ κόσμου) — "elemental powers of the world" — likely refers not merely to basic principles but to spiritual powers or cosmic entities that were understood in Second Temple Judaism to govern the nations and the material order (cf. Gal 4:3, 9; Deut 32:8 LXX). Paul contrasts these subordinate powers with the supreme authority of Christ.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Theotēs" (θεότητος, Strong\'s G2320) is a NT hapax distinct from "theiotēs" (Rom 1:20). Theotēs denotes the very essence and being of God—not merely divine qualities but the fullness of absolute Deity. "Sōmatikōs" (bodily) affirms that this divine fullness dwells in Christ in embodied, incarnate form—permanently, not temporarily. This is among the strongest Christological affirmations in the NT (cf. John 1:14; Col 1:19).',
        11: 'TYPOLOGY: The "circumcision not made with hands" fulfills the OT promise of the circumcision of the heart (Deut 30:6; Jer 4:4). The "putting off of the body of the flesh" (τῇ ἀπεκδύσει τοῦ σώματος τῆς σαρκός) echoes the stripping imagery used of the hostile powers in v.15, linking the believer\'s liberation to Christ\'s victory. GREEK: "Acheiropoiētos" (ἀχειροποίητος, G886) — "not made with hands" — contrasts the divine action with all human religious ritual (cf. Mark 14:58; 2 Cor 5:1).',
        14: 'GREEK: "Cheirographon" (χειρόγραφον, G5498) is a NT hapax meaning a handwritten document of debt — a legal certificate of indebtedness. "Dogmasin" (δόγμασιν) refers to the ordinances or decrees. THEOLOGICAL: The debt-document representing our obligation under the law is not merely canceled but nailed to the cross — a dramatic image of Christ\'s substitutionary death annulling the legal claim that stood against humanity (cf. Eph 2:14-15). TYPOLOGY: The nailing to the cross transforms the Roman instrument of condemnation into the instrument of liberation.',
        15: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Archas kai tas exousias" (τὰς ἀρχὰς καὶ τὰς ἐξουσίας) — "the rulers and the authorities" — refers to hostile spiritual powers in the divine council framework, not merely human rulers. Christ\'s cross is paradoxically his enthronement: the moment of apparent defeat is the moment of cosmic victory. "Apekdysamenos" (ἀπεκδυσάμενος, G554) means "having stripped/disarmed," portraying Christ as the divine warrior who despoils his enemies. "Thriambeusas" (θριαμβεύσας) evokes the Roman triumphal procession, displaying conquered enemies publicly (cf. 2 Cor 2:14).',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: The festivals, new moons, and sabbaths are declared to be a "shadow" (σκιά) of the coming realities, while the "body" (σῶμα) — the substance casting the shadow — belongs to Christ. This shadow-substance typology parallels Hebrews 8:5 and 10:1. The entire Israelite liturgical calendar finds its fulfillment and substance in the person and work of Christ.',
        18: 'GREEK: "Katabrabeuetō" (καταβραβευέτω, G2603) is a NT hapax meaning "to decide against as an umpire, to disqualify, to rob of a prize" — a term from athletic competition. "Thrēskeia tōn angelōn" (θρησκείᾳ τῶν ἀγγέλων) could be either subjective genitive ("worship that angels perform") or objective genitive ("worship directed toward angels"). DIVINE_COUNCIL: In Second Temple Jewish mystical tradition, angelic liturgy and visionary ascent practices were known (cf. Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice from Qumran). "Embateuōn" (ἐμβατεύων, G1687) likely refers to entering a heavenly sanctuary in visionary experience. Paul warns that such practices, disconnected from Christ the Head, are products of fleshly presumption.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Apethanete syn Christō" — "you died with Christ" — the believer\'s co-crucifixion with Christ severs the binding authority of the stoicheia (elemental powers). "Dogmatizesthe" (δογματίζεσθε, G1379) is a NT hapax meaning "to submit to decrees/regulations." The rhetorical question exposes the absurdity of those who, having been freed from cosmic powers through union with Christ\'s death, voluntarily re-enslave themselves to human religious regulations (cf. Gal 4:9).',
        23: 'GREEK: "Ethelothrēskia" (ἐθελοθρησκία, G1479) is a NT hapax meaning "self-imposed worship" or "would-be religion" — worship that originates in human will rather than divine command. "Apheidia sōmatos" (ἀφειδίᾳ σώματος) — "severe treatment of the body" — another rare term (G857, hapax). THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s conclusion is devastating: all such ascetic regulations possess an appearance (λόγον) of wisdom but have no actual value (οὐκ ἐν τιμῇ τινι) in restraining fleshly indulgence. External religion without Christ is powerless against the flesh.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Synēgerthēte" (συνηγέρθητε, Strong\'s G4891) is a compound verb: σύν (with) + ἐγείρω (raise). The aorist passive indicates a completed past event — believers\' co-resurrection with Christ is already accomplished in the divine economy. "Ta anō" (the things above) contrasts the heavenly realm with the earthly throughout vv. 1-4. THEOLOGICAL: Christ seated at God\'s right hand (Ps 110:1) establishes his cosmic kingship and the spatial orientation of the believer\'s new allegiance.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Apethanete" (you died) is aorist — a definitive past event linked to baptism (Col 2:12, 20). "Kekryptai" (κέκρυπται, G2928) is perfect passive — your life has been hidden and remains hidden. The hiddenness of the believer\'s true life in God provides both protection and mystery: the fullness of what believers are awaits eschatological unveiling (v. 4). TYPOLOGY: The hidden life echoes the theme of God concealing his people — as Israel was hidden in Egypt, so the church\'s life is concealed with Christ in the heavenly realm.',
        4: 'GREEK: "Phanerōthē" (φανερωθῇ, G5319) — "made manifest, revealed" — is used twice in this verse, first of Christ\'s appearing and then of believers\' co-manifestation. This is not merely "appearing" but an uncovering of hidden reality. THEOLOGICAL: This is a key eschatological text: the parousia of Christ will simultaneously reveal his glory and the glorified identity of his people (Rom 8:18-19; 1 John 3:2).',
        5: 'GREEK: "Nekrōsate" (νεκρώσατε, G3499) is an aorist imperative — a decisive, once-for-all putting to death. The list moves from outward acts (porneía, sexual immorality) to inward dispositions (evil desire) to root sin (pleonexía, covetousness). THEOLOGICAL: Paul identifies covetousness as "idolatry" (εἰδωλολατρία), linking disordered desire to worship of false gods — a striking connection between the moral and the cultic (Eph 5:5).',
        10: 'GREEK: "Anakainoumenon" (ἀνακαινούμενον, G341) is a present passive participle — the new man is being continuously renewed, indicating an ongoing process. "Kat\' eikona tou ktisantos" (according to the image of the one having created him) is a direct allusion to Gen 1:26-27 (LXX). TYPOLOGY: The new creation in Christ restores the image of God marred in Adam. The "full knowledge" (epignōsis, G1922) toward which renewal moves is not mere information but relational, participatory knowing of God.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse abolishes all ethnic, religious, cultural, and social distinctions as ultimate categories within the new humanity. "Christ is all things and in all" (ta panta kai en pasin Christos) is a stunning claim of Christ\'s totality — he fills every category and inhabits every member. HISTORICAL: The inclusion of "Scythian" is remarkable — Scythians were regarded as the lowest of barbarians in Greco-Roman estimation, yet even this distinction is dissolved in Christ.',
        14: 'GREEK: "Syndesmos tēs teleiotētos" (σύνδεσμος τῆς τελειότητος) — "the bond of perfection." Syndesmos (G4886) is that which binds together; teleiotēs (G5047) denotes completeness or maturity. Love (agapē) is the binding force that brings all the virtues of vv. 12-13 to their completion. THEOLOGICAL: Love is not merely one virtue among many but the integrating principle that perfects the whole — the capstone of the new humanity\'s moral life.',
        15: 'GREEK: "Brabeuetō" (βραβευέτω, G1018) means "let it act as umpire" or "let it rule as arbiter" — drawn from athletic contest language where a brabeus adjudicated the prize. This is a NT hapax legomenon. The peace of Christ is to be the decisive arbitrating authority in the hearts of believers and in community disputes. THEOLOGICAL: "In one body" (en heni sōmati) grounds the imperative ecclesiologically — peace rules because believers share one corporate body in Christ.',
        22: 'GREEK: "Ophthalmodouliais" (ὀφθαλμοδουλίαις, G3787) — "eye-service" — is a rare compound word, possibly coined by Paul, meaning service performed only when being watched. "Haplotēti kardias" (sincerity of heart) stands in contrast: an undivided, single-focused heart. HISTORICAL: The household codes (Haustafel, vv. 18-4:1) address the Roman household structure. Paul subverts its logic by directing the bondservant\'s ultimate allegiance to the Lord Christ, not the earthly master.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Tō kyriō Christō douleuete" — "The Lord Christ you serve" — may be read as indicative (you are serving) or imperative (serve!). Either way, it redefines servitude: the true Master of all bondservants is the Lord Christ. "Antapodosin tēs klēronomias" (the recompense of the inheritance) is remarkable — bondservants, who legally could inherit nothing in Roman law, are promised a divine inheritance. TYPOLOGY: This echoes Israel\'s inheritance of the promised land, now universalized as an eschatological reward from the Lord.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: κύριοι (kyrioi, Strong\'s G2962) here means "masters" in the social sense, while κύριον (kyrion) in the second clause refers to Christ as heavenly Master. The wordplay is deliberate — earthly masters are accountable to the ultimate Lord. ἰσότητα (isotēta, G2471) means "equality" or "fairness," a remarkable term in a slaveholding context. THEOLOGICAL: Paul subverts the master-slave hierarchy by establishing Christ\'s lordship over all human authority structures (Col 3:24-25; Eph 6:9).',
        3: 'GREEK: μυστήριον (mystērion, G3466) is a key Pauline term in Colossians, referring not to something unknowable but to God\'s previously hidden plan now revealed in Christ (Col 1:26-27; Eph 3:3-6). θύραν τοῦ λόγου ("door of the word") is a metaphor for gospel opportunity (cf. 1 Cor 16:9; 2 Cor 2:12). δέδεμαι (dedemai, perfect passive of δέω) indicates Paul\'s ongoing state of imprisonment at the time of writing.',
        5: 'GREEK: ἐξαγοραζόμενοι (exagorazomenoi, G1805) literally means "buying up" or "redeeming" the time (καιρόν, kairon — opportune season, not mere chronological time). The middle voice suggests personal investment. τοὺς ἔξω ("those outside") is a standard designation for non-believers (cf. 1 Cor 5:12-13; 1 Thess 4:12). THEOLOGICAL: Wisdom toward outsiders reflects the missionary posture of the early assembly.',
        6: 'GREEK: ἅλατι ἠρτυμένος ("seasoned with salt") — ἀρτύω (artyō, G741) means to season or prepare food. Salt (hálas, G217) signifies both preservation and flavor. This parallels Jesus\' teaching on salt in Matt 5:13 and Mark 9:50. THEOLOGICAL: Christian speech must be simultaneously gracious (ἐν χάριτι) and substantive, not bland — able to meet each individual\'s need.',
        9: 'HISTORICAL: Onesimus (Ὀνήσιμος, G3682, meaning "useful" or "profitable") is almost certainly the same runaway bondservant commended in Paul\'s epistle to Philemon. The phrase ὅς ἐστιν ἐξ ὑμῶν ("who is from among you") identifies him as a Colossian, linking this letter directly to Philemon\'s household. His designation as "faithful and beloved brother" publicly elevates his status before the entire assembly.',
        11: 'GREEK: παρηγορία (parēgoria, G3931) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, meaning "comfort" or "consolation." It was used in medical literature for soothing remedies. HISTORICAL: "These alone of the circumcision" indicates that only these three Jewish believers — Aristarchus, Mark, and Justus — were actively collaborating with Paul for the kingdom. The phrase βασιλείαν τοῦ θεοῦ ("kingdom of God") is rare in Paul\'s prison epistles, underscoring the royal-eschatological dimension of their mission.',
        15: 'HISTORICAL: Νύμφαν (Nymphan) with the pronoun αὐτῆς ("her") indicates a woman hosting a house-assembly in Laodicea. Some manuscripts read αὐτοῦ ("his"), reflecting later scribal discomfort with female ecclesial leadership. THEOLOGICAL: The κατ\' οἶκον ἐκκλησίαν ("assembly according to house") reflects the standard structure of early Christian worship before dedicated buildings existed (cf. Rom 16:5; 1 Cor 16:19; Phlm 1:2).',
        16: 'HISTORICAL: τὴν ἐκ Λαοδικείας ("the one from Laodicea") refers to an epistle circulating from Laodicea — its identity is debated. Some have identified it with Ephesians (which may have been a circular letter) or a now-lost Pauline letter. This instruction reveals the early practice of reading apostolic letters aloud in assembled worship and sharing them among neighboring congregations, anticipating the eventual canonical collection.',
        18: 'GREEK: τῇ ἐμῇ χειρί ("by my own hand") indicates Paul took the pen from his amanuensis to write the closing himself, authenticating the letter (cf. 1 Cor 16:21; Gal 6:11; 2 Thess 3:17). μνημονεύετέ μου τῶν δεσμῶν ("remember my bonds") — δεσμῶν (desmōn, G1199) denotes literal chains, a poignant final request connecting to the μυστήριον for which he is bound (4:3). The abrupt brevity of this closing is striking compared to other Pauline epistles.',
    },
}